[1]
Date: Tue 11 Oct 2005
From: Dave Knight <michmac9@hotmail.com>
Source: The Cape times, Mon 10 Oct 2005 [edited]
<http://capetimes.co.za/index.php?fSectionId=269&fArticleId=2939406>


A 46 year old southern Cape farm worker is in a critical
condition in Groote Schuur Hospital after contracting
Crimean-Congo haemorrhagic fever (CCHF). Those who contract
the virus have a 30 to 50 per cent chance of dying. Dozens
of others are affected, although the health department says
the outbreak is contained.

7 of the man's relatives and colleagues who came into
contact with him, and who have shown early symptoms of the
disease, have been admitted to Riversdale Hospital for
observation. The 7 include the man's wife, his child and
other farm workers. None of them has shown any bleeding.

A further 66 people, mainly health workers who treated the
man, are being monitored for symptoms twice daily for 21
days. They are from the Heidelberg Clinic, Riversdale
Hospital and the George Hospital. By last night none of them
had shown symptoms of the disease.

The man, who works on a cattle farm between Swellendam and
Heidelberg, was flown to Groote Schuur from the George
Regional Hospital last Wednesday [5 Oct 2005]. CCHF was
diagnosed on Friday [7 Oct 2005]. He is being treated in
isolation at Groote Schuur by medical staff wearing full
"space suit" protective clothing and masks. His symptoms are
high fever, vomiting, diarrhoea, muscular pain, coughing up
blood, and bleeding from the nose.

Keith Cloete, the acting chief director for health
programmes in the Department of Health, said yesterday the
department had set in motion its "full outbreak response"
and staff believed they had contained the disease. The staff
had also notified the department of Agriculture "We have
only one confirmed case of CCHF, a 46 year old man who works
on a cattle farm between Swellendam and Heidelberg," Cloete
said. "He is critical but stable. The diagnosis was
confirmed last Friday and we've traced back everyone who has
been in contact with him. There were 47 people in Riversdale
and we've admitted 7 of those as a precaution. The other 40
we are monitoring, taking their temperatures morning and
evening. If there is any suspicion that they have symptoms,
we will admit them. These 40 are mainly the hospital staff
who treated him." Another 26 people are being monitored in
George. They are also mainly hospital staff and emergency
medical staff. None has been admitted.

Cloete said the man had developed flu-like symptoms on 26
Sep 2005. On 3 Oct, he went to the clinic in Heidelberg,
which referred him to Riversdale Hospital. He was
transferred the next day to the bigger George Hospital,
where he began bleeding. Blood tests howed "problems with
his platelets" and he was flown to Groote Schuur for
specialist treatment. The disease, which is carried by ticks
infected with the virus, can spread from an infected person
to another by body fluids penetrating broken skin. It can
also spread to humans from the blood or tissue of fresh
animal carcasses infected with CCHF virus. People at higher
risk of getting CCHF are abattoir workers and people dealing
with livestock.

It is possible, but rare, for CCHF virus to be transmitted
to humans by bites from infected ticks. The tick that
carries the fever comes from the genus _Hyalomma_, found in
Africa, Asia and eastern Europe. Locally they are known as
bontpootluise.

[byline: Melanie Gosling]

--
Dave Knight
