[The 1st case of CCHF in South Africa was diagnosed in 1981
when the virus was isolated from the blood of a schoolboy
who died after being bitten by a tick in the North West
Province. This prompted investigations to determine the
prevalence of the virus in the country. Results of antibody
surveys on sera from humans, livestock and wild vertebrates
confirmed that the virus is widespread in South Africa in
areas corresponding to the distribution of ticks belonging
to the genus _Hyalomma_. The wide distribution of antibody
and its detection in sera which had been stored for several
years indicated that the virus had been present for many
years and was not a recent introduction. Information about
CCHF in South Africa is available on the South African
government's website: <http://www.info.gov.za>.

CCHF cases are rare but can be fatal in humans. Animals are
less severely affected or unaffected by exposure to CCHF
virus. - Mod.CP]
